No, that "fingerprint" is just a security check to confirm you are connecting to the correct computer; it doesn't replace your password.
"SSH Keys" are a pair of special files (a lock and a key) that allow your machines to talk to each other without ever typing or sending a password over the network.
How to set up "Bulletproof" SSH Keys
Run these commands on your source machine:
Generate your key:
bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519
Use code with caution.
Press Enter for everything (no passphrase needed for simple home use).
Send the key to your backup machine:
bash
ssh-copy-id rais@192.168.1.4
Use code with caution.
Type your password one last time.
Test it:
bash
ssh rais@192.168.1.4
Use code with caution.
You should log in instantly without a password.

Why this is safer
No Password Brute-forcing: Even if a hacker got onto your LAN, they can't guess a "password" because there isn't one—only the machine with your physical "key" file can enter.
Disable Passwords: Once this works, you can tell SSH to refuse all passwords entirely.
Secure your setup (Optional)
To make it truly "bulletproof," edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config on the destination machine and change these lines:
PasswordAuthentication no
PermitRootLogin no
Then run sudo systemctl restart sshd. Now, the only way into that machine via SSH is with your specific key file.
